<dl id="n53078a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53078a">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53078a"> 78(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Sheldru <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53078a"><li>FW 338.21 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53078a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53078a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53078a">MS BL 47480-38v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:072 <a name="mdd4" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd4.htm#n53078a">Draft: II.3&sect;4.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Following Leland, who first popularized the name, the language is usually called &lsquo;Shelta&rsquo;. This, however, is not quite accurate. The right name is &lsquo;<mark>Sheldr&uacute;</mark>&rsquo; or &lsquo;Shelot&uacute;&rsquo;, &lsquo;Shelta&rsquo; being a corruption due to imperfect speech or hearing. Other variants are &lsquo;Shelter&rsquo; or &lsquo;Sheltero&chi;&rsquo; &mdash; all being perversions of the Irish <i>b&eacute;lra</i> or <i>b&eacute;rla</i>, in modern spelling <i>b&eacute;arla</i>, meaning &lsquo;speech, language, jargon&rsquo;, and now most commonly, though not exclusively, used in the sense of &lsquo;English&rsquo;. <small> R.A. Stewart MacAlister, <a name="MSLI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MSLI"><cite title="source">The Secret Languages of Ireland</cite></a> (Jan 1937) Shelta, 137</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
